<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20
<div class=3D"video"><a><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/style=
/video.svg" alt=3D"Video" style=3D"width:56px; height:49px;vertical-align:m=
iddle; border:none;"></a><span id=3D"video0" style=3D""></span></div>


<h1 class=3D"center">Polynomials</h1>=20


<p class=3D"larger">A polynomial looks like this:</p>=20
<div class=3D"beach">

	<table class=3D"center" style=3D"border-spacing: 5px;">
		<tbody><tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/polynomial-exa=
mple.svg" alt=3D"polynomial example" height=3D"97" width=3D"197"></td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>example of a polynomial<br>
this one has 3 terms</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"words">=20
<p><b>Polynomial</b> comes from <i>poly-</i> (meaning "many") and <i>-nomia=
l</i> (in this case meaning "term") ... so it says "many terms"</p>=20
</div>
<p>Polynomials with one variable make nice smooth curves:</p>=20
<p><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/sage-walks-poly.sv=
g" alt=3D"algebra girl" height=3D"226" width=3D"635"></p>=20
<p class=3D"larger" style=3D"margin-top:-40px;">A polynomial can have:</p>=
=20
<ul class=3D"larger">=20
	<li><b><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/definitions.html">con=
stants</a></b> (like <b>3</b>, <b>=E2=88=9220</b>, or <b>=C2=BD</b>)</li>=
=20
	<li><b><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/definitions.html">var=
iables</a></b> (like <i><b>x</b></i> and <i><b>y</b></i>)</li>=20
	<li><b><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/exponent.html">exponents</a><=
/b> (like the 2 in y<sup>2</sup>), but only <b> 0, 1, 2, 3, ...</b> and so =
on are allowed</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p class=3D"large">that can be combined using <b>addition, subtraction, mul=
tiplication and division</b> ...</p>=20
<!--
<p class=3D"center larger">... except ...</p> -->=20
<p class=3D"center"><span class=3D"larger">... but <b>not</b> division by a=
 variable</span> (so something like <b>2/x</b> is right out)</p>=20
<p>So:</p>=20
<div class=3D"def">=20
<p class=3D"center">A polynomial can have constants, variables and exponent=
s,<br>
but never division by a variable.</p>=20
</div>=20

<p>Also they can have one or more terms, but not an <a href=3D"https://www.=
mathsisfun.com/numbers/infinity.html">infinite</a> number of terms.</p>=20


<h2>Polynomial or Not?</h2>=20

<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/p=
olynomial.svg" alt=3D"polynomial" height=3D"192" width=3D"463"></p>=20
<p>These <b>are</b> polynomials:</p>=20
<ul class=3D"large">=20
	<li><b>3x</b></li>=20
	<li><b>x =E2=88=92 2</b></li>=20
	<li><b>=E2=88=926y<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 (<span class=3D"f"><u>7</u><em>9<=
/em></span>)x</b></li>=20
	<li><b>3xyz + 3xy<sup>2</sup>z =E2=88=92 0,1xz =E2=88=92 200y + 0,5</b></l=
i>=20
	<li><b>512v<sup>5</sup></b> + <b>99w<sup>5</sup></b></li>=20
	<li><b>5</b></li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>(Yes, "5" is a polynomial, <b>one term is allowed</b>, and it can be jus=
t a constant!)</p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<p>These are <b>not</b> polynomials</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li><b>3xy<sup>-2</sup></b> is not, because the exponent is "-2" (exponent=
s can only be 0,1,2,...)</li>=20
	<li><b>2/(x+2)</b> is not, because dividing by a variable is not allowed</=
li>=20
	<li><b>1/x</b> is not either</li>=20
	<li><b>=E2=88=9Ax</b> is not, because the exponent is "=C2=BD" (see <a hre=
f=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/exponent-fractional.html">fractiona=
l exponents</a>)</li>=20
</ul>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<p><b>But</b> these <b> are</b> allowed:</p>=20
<ul class=3D"large">=20
	<li><b>x/2</b> <b>is allowed</b>, because we can divide by a constant</li>=
=20
	<li>also <b>3x/8</b> for the same reason</li>=20
	<li><b>=E2=88=9A2</b> is allowed, because it is a constant (=3D 1,4142... =
and so on)</li>=20
</ul>=20


<h2>Monomial, Binomial, Trinomial</h2>=20

<p>There are special names for polynomials with 1, 2 or 3 terms:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/p=
olynomials.svg" alt=3D"monomial, binomial, trinomial" height=3D"59" width=
=3D"529"></p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><i><b>How do you remember the names? Think cycles!<br>
<br></b> </i>  <img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/mono-b=
i-tri.svg" alt=3D"monocycle bicycle tricycle" height=3D"121" width=3D"388">=
</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><i>There is also quadrinomial (4 terms) and quintinomia=
l (5 terms),<br>
but those names are not often used.</i></p>=20


<h2>Variables</h2>=20

<p>Polynomials can have no variable at all</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p>Example: <span class=3D"large">21</span> is a polynomial. It has just o=
ne term, which is a constant.</p>=20
	</div>
<p>Or one variable</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p>Example: <span class=3D"large">x<sup>4 </sup>=E2=88=92 2x<sup>2 </sup>+=
 x</span> has three terms, but only one variable (x)</p>=20
	</div>
<p>Or two or more variables</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p>Example: <span class=3D"large">xy<sup>4 </sup>=E2=88=92 5x<sup>2</sup>z=
</span> has two terms, and three variables (x, y and z)</p>=20
	</div>


<h2>What is Special About Polynomials?</h2>=20

<p>Because of the strict definition, polynomials are <b>easy to work with</=
b>.</p>=20
<p>For example we know that:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>when we <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polynomials-addi=
ng-subtracting.html">add polynomials</a> we get a polynomial</li>=20
	<li>when we <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polynomials-mult=
iplying.html">multiply polynomials</a> we get a polynomial</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>So we can do lots of additions and multiplications, and still have a pol=
ynomial as the result.</p>=20
<p>Also, polynomials of one variable are easy to graph, as they have smooth=
 and continuous lines.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: <span class=3D"large">x<sup>4</sup>=E2=88=922x<sup>2</sup>+x<=
/span></h3>=20

	<div class=3D"example2">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/polynomial-tur=
ning-points1.gif" alt=3D"x^4-2x^2+x" height=3D"212" width=3D"216"></td>
			<td>=20
	<p>See how nice and<br>
smooth the curve is?</p></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

</div>=20

<p>We can also <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polynomials-di=
viding.html">divide polynomials</a> (but the result may not be a polynomial=
).</p>=20


<h2>Degree</h2>=20

<p>The <b>degree</b> of a polynomial with only one variable is the <b>large=
st exponent</b> of that variable.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example:</h3>=20

	<div class=3D"two">=20
	<div class=3D"lt">4x<sup>3</sup> =E2=88=92 x + 2</div>
<div class=3D"rt">The Degree is <b>3</b> (the largest exponent of <span cla=
ss=3D"times"><i>x</i></span>)</div>

</div>=20

</div>=20

<p>Every term has a degree!</p>=20
<p>We <b>can</b> (but usually don't) write a polynomial like above with eve=
ry degree shown, like this:</p>=20
<div class=3D"center larger">4x<sup>3</sup> =E2=88=92 x<sup>1</sup> + 2x<su=
p>0</sup></div>

<p>Because</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>x<sup>1</sup> is simply x</li>=20
	<li>x<sup>0</sup> is simply 1, so 2x<sup>0</sup> is 2 =C3=97 1 =3D 2</li>=
=20
</ul>=20
<p>Learn more at <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/degree-expre=
ssion.html">Degree (of an Expression)</a>.</p>=20


<h2>Standard Form</h2>=20

<p>The <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/standard-form.html">St=
andard Form</a> for writing a polynomial is to put the terms with the highe=
st degree first.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Put this in Standard Form: 3<b>x<sup>2</sup></b> =E2=88=92 7 =
+ 4<b>x<sup>3</sup></b> + <b>x<sup>6</sup></b></h3>=20

	<p>The highest degree is 6, so that goes first, then 3, 2 and then the con=
stant last:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center large"><b>x<sup>6</sup></b> + 4<b>x<sup>3</sup></b> + 3=
<b>x<sup>2</sup></b> =E2=88=92 7</p>=20
</div>=20

<p>When a polynomial is written in Standard Form, the first term is called =
the <b>leading term</b>, and its number part is the <b>leading coefficient<=
/b>.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p>In our example the leading term is <b>x<sup>6</sup></b>, and its leadin=
g coefficient is <b>1</b> (because <b>x<sup>6</sup></b> really means <b>1x<=
sup>6</sup></b>).</p>=20
	</div>

<p>You <b>don't have to</b> use Standard Form, but it helps.</p>=20
<div class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/sage/s=
age-lying.png" alt=3D"happy sage" height=3D"244" width=3D"200"></div>

<div class=3D"gap"></div>

